1 provided for in 15-8-201 and the prior 9 years, but the average must exclude the lowest and highest yearly data
2 in the period.
3 (3) (a) The value change factor is the sum of the income change factor, weighted by 50%, the
4 gross profit margin change factor, weighted by 25%, and the property change factor, weighted by 25%.
5 (b) The income change factor is determined by dividing the change in earnings by the change in
6 the capitalization rate.
7 (c) The gross profit margin change factor is determined by dividing the average gross profit margin
8 for the 2 years immediately preceding the current tax year by the average gross profit margin for the 2 years
9 immediately preceding the previous tax year.
10 (d) The property change factor is determined by dividing the system cost reported by the railroad
11 for the tax year immediately preceding the current tax year by the system cost reported by the railroad for the
12 tax year immediately preceding the previous tax year.
13 (4) The department shall apportion the system value of the railroad to Montana by multiplying the
14 system value of the railroad determined under subsection (2) by the average of the allocation factor for the 2
15 years immediately preceding the current tax year. The allocation factor is determined under subsection (5).
16 (5) The allocation factor used to apportion the system value of the railroad to Montana is the
17 average of the sum of:
18 (a) the ratio of track miles in the state to total system track miles;
19 (b) the ratio of revenue ton miles in the state to total system revenue ton miles;
20 (c) the ratio of gross investment in road and equipment in the state to total system gross
21 investment in road and equipment;
22 (d) the ratio of operating revenue reported in the state to total system operating revenue; and
23 (e) the ratio of railroad car and locomotive miles in the state to total system railroad car and
24 locomotive miles.
25 (6) The department shall take into account extenuating circumstances to adjust the assessed
26 value of railroad property in the state. Occurrences that may result in an adjustment to the assessed value of
27 railroad property include but are not limited to:
28 (a) extraordinary, unusual, or infrequent events that are material in nature and of a character
